column168: Description Of Events

WHILE AT A TRUCK STOP FUEL ISLAND, HE OBSERVED LIQUID LEAKING FROM HIS TRAILER.  HE INVESTIGATED AND FOUND A DRUM LEAKING FROM ITS BOTTOM, BUT HE CANNOT TELL WHAT IS DAMAGED ON THE DRUM.  HE PLACED SPILL CONTAINMENT BOOMS AROUND THE SPILLAGE TO CONTAIN IT AND NOTIFIED THE CARRIER'S ON-CALL HAZMAT SPECIALIST.  THE SPECIALIST ARRANGED TO HAVE A CONTRACTOR PROCEED TO THE SITE AND CONDUCT A CLEAN UP.  THE CONTRACTOR OVERPACKED THE DRUM, NOTING A CRACK IN ITS BOTTOM HEAD, BUT NO OBVIOUS CAUSE FOR THE CRACK.  THEY DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THE TRUCK STOP'S FUEL ISLAND.  THE VEHICLE WAS THEN ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON ITS WAY.
DURING LOADING A FORKLIFT PUNCTURED THE CONTAINER. MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND WILL BE DISPOSED PROPERLY

column168: DRIVER STARTED TO UNLOAD AT PPL HARPER STA. PUT PUMP INTO LOAD INSTEAD OF UNLOAD THIS RESULTED IN TRAILER OVERFILLING DRIVER REALIZED MISTAKE AND SHUTDOWN THE PUMP RETRAIN DRIVER IN PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURE.

DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS THE PIPING BETWEEN TWO CONNECTED USTS WAS CLOGGED THUS FUEL COULD NOT PASS BETWEEN DURING DELIVERY. AS A RESULT, OVERFILL OCCURRED. DRIVER INPLEMENTED CLEANUP AND FACILITY PROVIDED DRUMS TO PUT WASTE. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR INDUSTRIAL MARINE RESPONDED AND ASSISTED DRIVER IN THE CLEANUP.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY IN CHATTANOOGA, TENNESSEE, THE HOSE ON THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC.'S SEVEN THOUSAND GALLON METAL TANK TRUCK RUPTURED. APPROXIMATELY SIX GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED, ONE GALLON OF WHICH WAS CONTAINED AND FROZE INSIDE A CONCRETE RETAINING AREA AT THE FACILITY. THE REMAINING FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED INSIDE ONE, FIVE GALLON BUCKET. FACILITY PERSONNEL APPLIED ABSORBENTS TO THE FREE PRODUCT AND PERFORMED THE CLEANUP. ALL WASTE GENERATED WILL BE HELD AT THE FACILITY FOR DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DURING THE DELIVERY OF GASOLINE, THERE IS OVERFILL PROTECTION FOR THE STORAGE TANKS THAT SHOULD SHUT DELIVERY OFF WHEN THE STORAGE TANK REACHES 90% OF CAPACITY.  DURING THIS DELIVERY, THE OVERFILL PROTECTION FAILED TO FUNCTION AND WHEN THE TANK REACHED CAPACITY, GASOLINE WAS FORCED INTO THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE AND RESULTANTLY SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS ONTO THE PAVEMENT. EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO FUMES, CAUSING NAUSEA AND LIGHT-HEADEDNESS. THE EMPLOYEE VISITED A LOCAL CLINIC AND WAS CLEARED TO RETURN TO WORK. THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC, CONTACTED HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KANSAS TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP. HAZMAT ONE DISPATCHED FIRST RESPONSE, INC. OF NASHVILLE, TENNESSEE TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON INVESTIGATION, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED ON THE TOPS OF TWO, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY DRUMS AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CRYSTALLIZED ON THE TOPS OF THE DRUMS. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO OVERFILLING BY THE SHIPPER. FIRST RESPONSE, INC. CLEANED THE TOPS OF THE DRUMS. NO WASTE WAS GENERATED. THE TWO DRUMS WERE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE ON THE DOCK, THREE WET CARTONS EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON METAL CANS WERE DISCOVERED. UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO CANS WERE DAMAGED, TWO CANS WERE AFFECTED AND THE REMAINING EIGHT CANS WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY EIGHT OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE CANS WAS DUE TO BEING DROPPED DURING HANDLING. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, TYVEK SUITS AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, TWO DAMAGED CANS AND THREE WET CARTONS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE TWO AFFECTED CANS WERE CLEANED, RECOUPED WITH EIGHT UNAFFECTED CANS AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARDBOARD CARTON CONTAINING THREE, ONE GALLON METAL PAILS WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR THIRD OF THE TRAILER. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE AFFECTED PAIL WAS RECOUPED AND FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 80, IN RAVENNA, OHIO, THE DRIVER SWERVED OFF THE ROAD, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO HIT TREES ALONGSIDE THE ROADWAY AND OVERTURN INTO THE DITCH.  APPROXIMATELY 125 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WERE RELEASED FROM THE SADDLE TANKS ON THE VEHICLE.  THE PORTAGE COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY AND THE GARRETTSVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE.  SUNPRO, INC. OF NORTH CANTON, OHIO WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM CLEANUP.  SUNPRO, INC. PUMPED THE REMAINING DIESEL FUEL FROM THE DAMAGED SADDLE TANKS AND PLACED THE FREE LIQUID INTO ONE (1) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM.  SUNPRO, INC. PROCEEDED TO REMOVE, AND INSPECT ALL FREIGHT FROM THE TRAILER.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER, SUNPRO, INC. DISCOVERED APPROXIMATELY 10 DAMAGED FIVE-GALLON DRUMS WHICH HAD BEEN DENTED OR LOST THEIR LIDS DUE TO THE IMPACT FROM THE ACCIDENT.  APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF FREE LIQUID WERE RELEASED.  SUNPRO, INC. RECOUPED THE DAMAGED DRUMS INTO EIGHT (8) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS WHICH WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER, EUCLID CHEMICAL, FOR DISPOSITION.  SUNPRO, INC. ALSO COORDINATED CLEANUP OF THE DIESEL FUEL IMPACTED SOIL ALONG WITH THE OHIO TURNPIKE COMMISSION.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.

column168: ON 1/15/03 AT 1400 HOURS CN MECHANICAL FOREMAN GABE BROBERG, JACKSON, MS REPORTED VICX2401, ENVIRONMENTAL HAZARD, WAS LEAKING IN TRACK 1A NORTH YARD. AT THE CAR IN QUESTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DOME LID WAS OPEN. THERE WAS NO BROKEN SEAL FOUND. SOME OF THE PRODUCT HAD SPLASHED OUT OF THE TOP OF THE CAR AND ONTO THE SIDE OF SAME. THE LID WAS CLOSED AND BOLTS WERE SECURED. LOSS APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS. LIME WAS PLACED BENEATH WHERE THE CAR HAD BEEN SITTING. THE CAR WAS BAD ORDERED TO THE LOCOMOTIVE FACILITY WHERE SAME WAS WASHED OFF. VICTOR GARCIA WITH THE TEX MEX RAILWAY IN LAREDO, TX WAS ADVISED. AL RAWLS WITH THE KCS RAILWAY WAS ADVISED. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THIS CAR WAS RECEIVED FROM THE KCS RAILROAD IN JACKSON IN THIS CONDITION.***INCIDENT SEVERITY INDEX 5(5+1+5)(3+2)=275. **CAUSE CODE 275*

THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND TWO LEAKING METAL PAILS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING TWO HUNDRED AND SEVENTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC TOTE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER AND DOCK FLOOR.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A SHIPPER ERROR, THE TOTE WAS OVERFILLED.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, ABSORBENTS AND AMPHOMAG.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING TOTE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD IN THE TERMINALS HAZMAT BAY AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, FOUR LITER GLASS JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE JUG WAS DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING THREE JUGS WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY FOUR LITERS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND EVAPORATED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE JUGS WAS DUE TO THE CARTON BEING DROPPED DURING HANDLING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED JUG WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE THREE UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE RECOUPED IN THE ORIGINAL PACKAGING AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND WAS CONTAINED TO THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING RESPIRATORS, ABSORBENTS, AND GLOVES.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE LOOSE BUNG ON THE DRUM WAS TIGHTENED, AND THE DRUM ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING SIX, ONE GALLON STEEL CANS WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE CAN WAS DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING FIVE CANS WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE CAN WAS DUE TO THE FREIGHT BEING DAMAGED DURING LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND DAMAGED CAN WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE FIVE UNAFFECTED CANS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON OVERPACK DRUM AND WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THERE WAS ONE EXPOSURE REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE BUT NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS REQUIRED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE LOADING THE TRAILER ONE FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL OF PRODUCT WAS CRUSHED BETWEEN TWO PALLETS RELEASING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS TO THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER AND THE DOCK.  THE PRODUCT WAS LOCATED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. CLEAN UP WAS PERFORMED BY ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. HAZMAT PERSONNEL USING GLOVES, ABSORBENTS AND SHOVELS.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIAL AND FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A 35 GALLON FIBER DRUM LINED WITH PLASTIC.  THE 35 GALLON FIBER DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSITION.   MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  NO AGENCIES WERE ON SCENE.

WHILE ATTEMPTING TO VACUUM MATERIAL FROM CUSTOMER TANK TO TRANSPORT TRAILER, THE REDUCING FITTING USED AT THE TRUCK CONNECTION FAILED, ALLOWING THE HOSE TO FALL TO THE GROUND.  APPROX 10 GAL OF MATERIAL TO SPILL ON THE GROUND.  THE FITTING FAILED DUE TO THE INCOMPATIBILITY OF THE MATERIAL OF CONSTRUCTION OF THE FITTING (STEEL & ALUMINUM) AND THE MATERIAL BEING LOADED (FERRIC CHLORIDE).   UPON DISCOVERY OF THE FAILURE, THE LOADING PROCEDURE WAS STOPPED.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS WHOLLY CONTAINED ON THE LOADING PAD.  THE ON-SITE RESPONSE TEAM CLEANED THE SPILLED MATERIAL WITH OIL-DRY MIXTURE AND PLACED THE CLEAN UP MATERIAL IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR LATER DISPOSAL.  THE AREA WAS DECOMTAMINATED USING ASH SODA AND WATER.  THE FAILED FITTING WAS REPLACED AND THE LOADING COMPLETE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THE DRIVER WAS RETRAINED IN THE PROPER SELECTION OF FITTINGS IN REGARDS TO RESISTANCE TO THE MATERIAL BEING LOADED.  ONLY FITTINGS CONSTRUCTED OF STAINLESS STEEL OR PVC WILL BE USED WHEN LOADING FERRIC CHLORIDE.

THIS RAILCAR WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE TOP DURING REGULAR SWITCHING OPERATIONS. THIS RAILCAR WAS ISOLATED ON SHOP TRACK #3. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. DURING THEIR INVESTIGATION OF THE RELEASE, THE SHIPPER ADVISED THAT THE CAUSE TO THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE OPENING AND RECLOSING. THE SHIPPER ADVISED THAT THIS WAS DUE TO THE CARRIER HUMPING THE RAILCAR TO HARD. FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR, ED ERNEWEIN REQUESTED THAT THE RAILCAR BE RELEASED AT EXPLANATION FOR THE RELEASE. MR. ERNEWEIN RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. MR ERNEWEIN REQUESTED THAT THE RAILCAR BE RELEASED AT NORMAL SWITCHING SPEEDS AND ALLOWED TO COUPLE INTO STATIONARY RAILCARS. THE RAILCAR WAS RELEASED AT APPROX.3 MPH AND ALLOWED TO COUPLE INTO A STATIONARY CUT OF CARS. THE RELEASE WAS DETERMINED TO BE COMING FROM THE FLANGE BELOW THE SRV AND NOT THE SRV ITSELF. THE RAILCAR WAS ISOLATED AND REPAIRS WERE MADE ON THE FOLLOWING DAY. 01/23/03. INCIDENT SEVERITY INDEX-2(5+5+0)(2+0)=40 CAUSE CODE-409

THE IMPACT OF THE PAIL HITTING THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER CAUSED IT TO CRACK AND FLUID BEGAN TO LEAK OUT. THE PAIL WAS TIED TO THE TRAILER WITH ROPE BY ITS HANDLE BUT APPARENTLY IT WASN'T SECURED TIGHTLY. column168: WHILE LOADING AT OUR KANSAS CITY LOCATION A FORKLIFT BLADE PUNCTURED A HOLE IN ONE DRUM CAUSING IT TO LEAK APPROX. 6 GALLONS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIAL AND DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND IS BEING HELD FOR DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER.

THE DRIVER WAS OBSERVING HIS FLUID PERCENTAGE GUAGE FROM THE GROUND.  HE NOTICED THAT IT STUCK ON 70% FOR SAME TIME.  HE CLIMBED ON TOP OF THE TRAILER TO SHUT DOWN LOADING WHEN HE ARRIVED ON TOP, THE TRAILER STARTED TO OVERFILL.  HE SHUT IT DOWN.  HE OVERFILLED ABOUT 3 BARRELS AND IT SPILLED ON THE ICE UNDER HIS VEHICLE.  THE OIL WAS SHOVELED UP AND TAKEN TO A CERTIFIED DISPOSAL FACILITY FOR COLLECTION.

THE DRIVER WAS LOADING HIS TRAILER THROUGH THE BOTTOM USING A TRACTOR MOUNTED PUMP.  ASH WAS FILLING HIS TRAILER, THE FIVE VALVE ON THE LEAD TRAILER CLOSED, THIS CAUSED THE MAJORITY OF THE OIL TO BE PUSHED TO THE PULL TRAILER.  THE DRIVER WAS ON TOP OF HIS LEAD TRAILER WATCHING THE OIL COME UP TO HIS LOADED MARKS.  HE THEN NOTICED OIL COMING OUT OF THE OVERFLOW TUBE ON THE PULL TRAILER.   HE CLIMBED DOWN & STOPPED THE JUMPING PROCESS.  WE REMOVED THE SET UP OIL FROM UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER SO IT COULD BE MOVED.  A CLEANUP CREW CAME AND CLEANED TRAILER SO IT COULD BE MOVED.  A CLEANUP CREW CAME AND CLEANED THE LOCATION & TOOK THE CONTAMINATED OIL TO AN APPROVED DISPOSAL.

THE DRUM WAS UNDER A PALLET SUPPORTING IT'S WEIGHT.  WHEN THE DOCKWORKER WAS UNLOADING THE PALLET ON TOP, THE DRUM UNDERNEATH "THAT WAS ALREADY BENT AND BUCKLED", SNAGGED UNDER THE BOTTOM RUNNER OF THE PALLET CAUSING IT TO TEAR OPEN AND FALL OVER SPILLING ITS CONTENTS ON THE DOCK PLATFORM. CONTENTS WERE PICKED UP AND RECOUPED INTO TWO FIVE GALLON CONTAINERS. PICTURES AND REPORT SENT TO ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER FOR FOLLOW-UP.  ALSO RECOMMENDATION ON NOT USING THESE CONTAINERS TO SUPPORT WEIGHT OF PALLETS DURING TRANSIT.

column168: WHILE SWITCHING WITH FLATCAR, FEC 37176, IN THE IMERSON ROAD YARD (AKA DUVAL RAMP) IN JACKSONVILLE, FL, THE LOAD IN CONTAINER CMCU 202917 SHIFTED BURSTING THE DOORS AND DROPPING SEVERAL 55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS ONTO THE FLAT AND THE GROUND. SEVERAL OF THE DRUMS WERE CAUGHT UP UNDER THE RAILCAR. THE SWITCH CREW REPORTED A STRONG ODOR AND AT LEAST 2 DRUMS WERE RUPTURED. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM WAS NOTIFIED. CSX TRANSPORTATION RESPONDED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DIRECTOR AND A PROFESSIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR. THE IMMEDIATE AREA WAS ISOLATED. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER, BUT THE SHIPPER OF RECORD WAS NOT LISTED. CSX INTERMODAL DETERMINED THAT US AMINES (FORMERLY CELANESE) WAS THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC MADE NOTIFICATION. CSXT'S RESPONSE CONTRACTOR INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND FOUND THAT DRUMS WERE DOUBLE STACKED WITH 2 BANDS OF "TYGUARD" ON THE TOP & BOTTOM LAYERS TO RESTRAIN THE LOAD. THE CONTRACTOR FOUND 12 DRUMS WERE EITHER LEAKING OR EMPTY AND 8 ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE DAMAGED. THE DAMAGED & LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED IN 85 GAL OVERPACKS. THE AREA WHERE THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLED WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH ACETIC ACID WITH THE AGREEMENT OF THE FLORIDA DEPT OF EVIRONMENT. CMCU 202917 WAS "DERAMPED" AND THE LOAD WAS ADJUSTED. THE 9 OVERPACKED DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED ON THE CONTAINER; THE CONTAINER WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED AND WILL BE SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER, US AMINES, FOR REPACKING. THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE LEAKING DRUMS WILL BE PROCESSED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: COVERED HOPPER, SHPX 432215, LOAD SODIUM CHLORATE, WAS DERAILED IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S (CSXT) RAIL YARD IN THOMASVILLE, GA. THE CAR HAD THE BOTTOM OF TWO (2) OF THE HOPPER CHUTES TORN WHEN IT SLID OVER THE BALL OF THE RAIL DURING THE DERAILMANT. THIS TEARING OF THE CHUTES ALLOWED, APPROXIMATELY 200 POUNDS OF PRODUCT, TO BE RELEASED. A PROFESSIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED AT THE REQUEST OF CXST'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SYSTEMS DEPARTMENT TO PLUG/PATCH THE HOLE AND TO REMOVE THE SPILLED PRODUCT. THE SHIPPER, KERR MCGEE CHEMICAL, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. BOTH THE "A" AND "B" HOPPER DISCHARGE TUBES WERE COVERED OVER WITH 1/8 INCH METAL COVERS THAT WERE FORMED AND WELDED IN POSITION. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED FROM THE TRACK BED AND WILL BE TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE SHIPPER FOR RECOVERY/REPROCESSING.

column168: DURING UNLOADING CUSTOMER TANK OVERFLOWED. CONSIGNEE HANDLED THE CLEANUP.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: AIRING OFF PRODUCT-PRODUCT STARTED LEAKING FROM THE PINS INSIDE INTERNAL VALVE. CONSIGNEE CLEANED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: IV TOOK A SAMPLE FOR THE CUSTOMER. HE CLOSED THE VALVE AFTER THE SAMPLE WAS COMPLETE. WHEN IV WAS HOOKING UP HIS HOSE HE NOTICED THAT THE VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED ALL THE WAY CAUSING PRODUCT TO SPILL. SOME GOT ON IV DRIVER. DRIVER HAD ON ALL PPE GEAR, NO INJURIES SUSTAINED, NO MEDICAL TREATMENT SOUGHT. SPILL WAS CLEANED BY DRIVER AND CONSIGNEE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK GUAGE MALFUNCTIONED AND STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED. CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP SPILL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER UNLOADED PRODUCT INTO CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK, WHICH WAS FULL. DRIVER PULLED HOSE FROM STORAGE TANK AND PRODUCT SPILLED OUT OF HOSE. SPILL CLEANED UP BY CONSIGNEE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: FREIGHT WAS REFUSED FOR TIME AND ITEM LEFT AT GATE E9. UPON RETURN TO CARGO FACILITY CARDBOARD BOX CONTAINING TOULENE ACETONE MIXTURE WAS FOUND TO BE CRUSHED AND LEAKING. EXAMINATION OF THE PACKAGE SHOWS CARDBOARD BOX WAS CRUSHED RESULTING IN A TUBE OF TOULENE ACETONE MIXTURE RUPTURING- .1 L OF TOULENE ACETONE MIXTURE WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE CARDBOARD BOX PACKAGING. SUSPECT BOX WAS CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT. WHEN CLEARED BY FAA TOULENE ACETONE MIXTURE, WHICH IS NOW DRY, WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN ESTABLISHED PAINT SOLIDS WASTE STREAM.

DRIVER WAS AT CUSTOMER TO UNLOAD. HE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TAPING A SAMPLE FROM THE BOTTOM VALVE. HE OPENED THE EXTERNAL VALVE A LITTLE. HE PUMP OPEN THE INTERNAL VALVE AND NOTHING CAME OUT. HE CLOSED IT AND OPENED IT AGAIN AND APPROX. 5 TO 10 GAL RAN OUT IN THE LOADING PAD. SOME OF THE PRODUCT WENT INTO THE PLANT DRAIN IN A SUMP TANK. THE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED OUT OF SUMP.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE TOTE WAS FOUND LEAKING. THE TOTE WAS LEAKING FROM THE SEAL UNDER THE CLOSURE LID ON THE TOP. THE CONSIGNEE SENT AN EMPLOYEE TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY TO REPLACE THE LID AND SEAL. THE TOTE DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THEIR WAS NO CLEAN-UP NEEDED DUE TO THE SPILLED PRODUCT DRYING.

WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, THE TOPS OF SEVERAL DRUMS WERE FOUND WET AND AN ODOR WAS NOTICEABLE AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER CONTACTED OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT WHO IN TURN CONTRACTED A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY TO ASSIST AT THE CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION. THE RESPONSE COMPANY FOUND THAT SEVERAL OF THE DRUMS HAD LOOSE BUNGS IN THE TOP THAT ALLOWED LIQUID TO SEEP AND WET THE TOPS OF THE DRUMS. THE RESPONSE COMPANY TIGHTED ALL THE BUNGS, WIPED THE DRUMS CLEAN, OFF-LOADED THE MATERIAL, AND PACKAGED THE CLEANUP MATERIAL FOR HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL. INTEGRITY OF THE DRUMS WAS FOUND INTACT.

THE LOADER FAILED TO CLOSE THE BLEEDER VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK AFTER THE TANK HAD BEEN LOADED. WHEN THE DRIVER PULLED AWAY PRODUCT SPILLED FROM THE BLEEDER VALVE AREA. THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON THE PAVEMENT AND WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND CLEANED UP. THERE WHERE NO INJURIES AND NO FURTHER INCIDENT.
UNSECURED PLT FELL OVER IN TRANSIT. BAG TORN ON DOOR HINGES.

WIRE CARRY HANDLE ON PAIL PULLED OUT/LOOSE FROM PAIL, DURING TRANSPORT. SMALL AMOUNT ON LIQUID, DICHLOROMETHANE, LEAKED FROM HOLE IN PAIL ONTO TRAILER FLOOR. PAIL WAS SECURED WITH ROPE DURING TRANSIT. PREVIOUS TRANSPORT OF THIS MATERIAL, IN THIS TYPE CONTAINER HAVE EXPERIENCED NO SIMILAR PROBLEM.

BNSF TRAIN INSPECTION REVEALED CONTAINER ENTRAINED ATOP INTERMODAL FLATCAR LEAKING PRODUCT & IT WAS SET OUT FROM TRAIN OVER CONTAINMENT PIT. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT CARDBOARD LAYER SEPARATOR BETWEEN DRUMS LAYERS NON-RECOMMENDED & INADEQUATE. DRUM SUSTAINED CUTS TO UPPER/BOTTOM CHIMES FROM DRUM ROTATION/MOVEMENT AT LAYER CONTACT POINTS. DAMAGED DRUMS OVERPACKED & ENTIRE LOAD RETURNED TO ORIGIN SHIPPER IN ANOTHER SHIPPING CONTAINER. SPILLED PRODUCT REMEDIATED.

THE VENT ON A BURIED 4000 GALLON TANK WAS BAD CAUSING OVER PRESSURE. WHEN THE DRIVER STOPPED PUMPING ABOUT 1 GALLON SPRAYED OUT OF THE FILL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP THERE WASN'T ANY OIL ENTERING STORM DRAINS OR STREAMS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE DRIVER WAS ENROUTE TO THE CUSTOMER AND HAD STOPPED A COUPLE OF TIMES TO CHECK THE TRAILER. HE STOPPED AT A TRUCK STOP TO EAT AND WHEN HE RETURNED, HE NOTICED A DRIP COMING FROM THE BELLY OF THE TRAILER AND REALIZED IT WAS PRODUCT. HE IMMEDIATELY PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP AND PROCEEDED TO CHECK ALL OF THE TANK'S OPENING AND FOUND NOTHING LOOSE OR LEAKING. HE THEN CALLED HIS DOMICILED TERMINAL, AND THE PROCESS WAS STARTED TO RECTIFY THE SITUATION. APPROXIMATELY 1/4-1/2 CUP HIT THE GROUND BEFORE THE BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK.
WHILE UNLOADING, NINE PAILS WERE PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT.  THE PAILS WERE RECOUPED INTO DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUMS WITH CHEMICAL LINERS, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: BNSF INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION IN RAIL YARD REVEALED TANK CAR LEAKING PRODUCT FROM TOP FLANGE PLATE AREA OF LIQUID & VAPOR LINE VALVES.  BNSF RESPONDER FOUND VALVES SECURE, BUT LITTLE PRODUCT OUTAGE EVIDENT DUE TO POSSIBLE OVERFILL/PRODUCT EXPANSION.  ON 1/31/03, APPROX. 2000-3000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS OFF-LOADED INTO A TANKER TRUCK (FOR DELIVERY TO CONSIGNEE) WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  TANK CAR RELEASED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION AFTERWARDS. DRIVER FILLED THE TRAILER WITH PRODUCT, AND THEN DECIDED TO PERFORM A QUALITY CHECK ON THE PRODUCT. WALKING AROUND THE BACK OF THE TRAILER, HE NOTICED A LEAK ON THE SIDE OF THE MANHOLE COVER. HE DETERMINED THE EXTENT OF THE LEAK AND NOTIFIED THE CORPORATE OFFICE PER OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN. ANOTHER DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE WITH ANOTHER TRAILER TO OFFLOAD THE MATERIAL FROM THIS ONE. THE TRAILER STOPPED LEAKING ONCE THE LIQUID LEVEL WAS BELOW THE LEAK POINT. THE TRAILER WAS EVACUATED AND SENT OUT FOR REPAIR. THERE WERE NO COMPLAINTS OF AMMONIA ODOR AND NO EVACUATIONS WERE MADE. LESS THAN 5 POUNDS OF AMMONIA WAS RELEASED. THIS TRAILER HAD BEEN IN FOR SERVICE PREVIOUSLY, AND THE MANHOLE GASKET REPLACED WITH A NEOPRENE ONE AND SOME MANHOLE BOLTS WERE ALSO REPLACED. UPON INVESTIGATING THIS INCIDENT, THE GASKET APPEARED TO HAVE FAILED, BUT THE SHOP PERSONNEL HAVE NOT DETERMINED A ROOT CAUSE.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE THIRD-QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE JUG WAS DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING THREE JUGS WERE AFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE JUG WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON, ONE DAMAGED JUG AND THREE AFFECTED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY RUM, ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER DRUM AND ONE FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. ALL THREE DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: OPERATOR WENT TO UNLOAD THE RAIL CAR WHEN HE NOTICED AN AMMONIA ODOR.  HE DONNED HIS PPE AND STARTED TO OPEN THE RAIL CAR DOME.  HE OBSERVED AMMONIA LEAKING FROM A VALVE.  HE REMOVED HIMSELF FROM THE AREA AND NOTIFIED THE CORPORATE OFFICE, PER OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  HARFORD COUNTY LEPC AND THE HAZMAT TEAM, ALONG WITH THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  THE HAZMAT TEAM IDENTIFIED THE LEAK SOURCE AS THE PACKING NUTS ON THE "B" VALVE.  THEY WERE MISALIGNED.  THE HAZMAT TEAM STRAIGHTENED THEM OUT AND TIGHTENED THEM, STOPPING THE LEAK.  THE RAIL CAR WAS COMPLETELY UNLOADED.  THERE WERE NO COMPLAINTS OF AMMONIA ODOR, AND NO EVACUATIONS WERE MADE.  APPROXIMATELY 10 POUNDS OF AMMONIA WERE RELEASED.

column168: BOISE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE TRAILER AND SAW THAT THE PALLET HE WAS UNLOADING HAD PUNCHED A 250 GALLON TOTE OF AMINES WHICH IS A CORROSIVE MATERIAL.  HE NOTIFIED THE MANAGER WHO CONTACTED HIS SAFETY SUPERVISOR. THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR TOLD THE LOCAL MANAGER TO KEEP ALL EMPLOYEES' AWAY FROM THE TRAILER AND TO CONTACT A PROFESSIONAL CLEAN UP CREW (OLYMPUS TECHNICAL SERVICES).  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY OLYMPUS AND  NONE OF THE CORROSIVE MATERIAL LEFT THE TRAILER.  DAMAGE TO THE TOTE WAS DUE FROM DUNNAGE (WOOD) STICKING INTO THE PLASTIC TOTE THAT WAS LOADED IN FRONT. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER.  THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE ONTO THE GROUND.  ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY PUMPED OFF THE TOTE INTO A CONTAINMENT BIN.

column168: WHILE IN TRANSIT, ONE DRUM WAS ABLE TO "WALK" TO THE EDGE OF THE PALLET IT WAS PLACED ON.  A DEFECTIVE BOARD ON THE PALLET FAILED, ALLOWING THE DRUM TO FALL TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. VIBRATIONS WHILE IN TRANSIT ALLOWED THE WRAP TO BECOME LOOSE.  THE DRUM THEN MOVED TO THE EDGE OF THE PALLET.  THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WAS STOPPED BY LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT DUE TO AN OBSERVED LEAK FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  HAZMAT TEAMS FROM THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED, UP RIGHTED THE FALLEN DRUM, PLACED IT IN AN OVERPACK CONTAINER.  THE RESIDUAL PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR RETAINED BY PRIME INC.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF SOIL ADJACENT TO THE ROADWAY WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF.  THE INTERSTATE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 3.5 HOURS.

HE AWOKE AND OVER CORRECTED, TURNING TO THE RIGHT CAUSING THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO OVERTURN ONTO THE DRIVER'S SIDE, WHERE IT SLID TO A STOP.  ACTION TAKEN AT TIME OF DISCOVERY  THE DRIVER WAS NOT SERIOUSLY HURT, HE EXTRICATED HIMSELF FROM THE WRECK AND CALLED 911, AND THE DISPATCH CENTER LOCATED IN PHOENIX, AZ  GASOLINE WAS SPILLING FROM UNIT, THE FIREMEN, HIGHWAY PATROL, AND AZ DEQ THAT RESPONDED CLOSED THE HIGHWAY AND KEPT EVERYONE AWAY UNTIL THE FUMES SUBSIDED. REMAINING FUEL WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER UNIT TO BE DELIVERED.  MP ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WERE CONTACTED TO REMOVE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND REPAIR THE SITE.  ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS, PICTURES WERE SHOWN AND AN EXPLANATION OF INCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED AT THE SAFETY MEETING DATED 3/5/03.  ALL DRIVERS OF THE COMPANY WERE SHOWN THE RESULTS OF FATIGUE, AND COUNSELED THAT THEY WERE EXPECTED TO SHOW UP TO WORK WITH THE PROPER REST NEEDED TO PERFORM THEIR JOBS SAFELY.

column168: ON JANUARY 30, 2003 AT APPROXIMATELY 1:  PM, LESS THAN 50 GALLONS OF RCRA K062 LISTED WASTED SPILLED DURING UNLOADING OF THE TANKOR TRUCK.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO HERITAGE'S PROPERTY AROUND THE ACID UNLOADING PAD.  THE SPILL OCCURRED ON ASPHALT THAT WAS COVERED IN SNOW AND ICE PACK.  THIS PREVENTED THE RELEASE FROM SIGNIFICANT TRAVEL.  ALL OF THE CONTAMINATED SNOW AND ICE WAS REMOVED, MELTED, AND PROCESSED IN THE FACILITY WASTE TREATMENT SYSTEM.  THE ASPHALT WAS POWERWASHED WITH HOT WATER, WHICH WAS ALSO PROCESSED IN THE WASTE TREATMENT SYSTEM.  AN INVESTIGATION OF THIS INCIDENT HAS DETERMINED THAT POOR COMMUNICATION BETWEEN TWO EMPLOYEES CAUSED THE SPILL.  DEPARTMENT SUPERVISORS CONDUCTED TRAINING TO RE-ENFORCE THE IMPORTANCE OF CLEAR COMMUNICATION.  THE TRAINING EMPHASIZED THE NEED FOR ADDITIONAL ATTENTION WHEN CO-WORKERS ARE WORKING TOGETHER ON THE SAME TASK.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT OF AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANK CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S  AMPTHILL, VA PLANT.  THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA, AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS IN QUESTION HAD EXPERIENCED ANY UNUSUAL HANDLING OR HARD COUPLING'S IN TRANSIT.  CSXT WITH OLIN'S CORPORATION HAD INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S. THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR.

column168: RICK SLOANE, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY TIM MORRIS, CAR FOREMAN, THAT TANK CAR PROX 40830 WAS SPLASHING METHANOL FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR WITH MOVEMENT.  THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN CONFINED IN THE YARD, ON DEPARTURE TRACK 301, NEAR 183 ON THE PORTLAND SUBDIVISION. THERE WERE NO REPORTS OF FATALITIES, INJURIES, EVACUATIONS OR LEAKS INTO WATERWAYS.  RMCC MADE NOTIFICATION TO ROB, CHEMTREC, AND WILLIAM AARDE, SPECIAL AGENT.  THE MANAGER MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE HAD ADVISED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE COMBINATION FITTINGS HOUSING, WAS CONTINUOUS, AND NOT SPLASHING.  THE LEAK WAS DESCRIBED AS A DRIBBLE.  MR. SLOANE RESPONDED AND HIS INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE PLUG IN THE LIQUID LINE VALVE.  THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED WITH SOME EFFORT AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF METHANOL WAS RELEASED TO THE TOP OF THE CAR AND RAPIDLY EVAPORATED.  LATER, ALL PRESSURE WAS RELEASED FROM THE CAR AND THE PLUG REMOVED AND TEFLON TAPED TO ENSURE NO FURTHER LEAKAGE.  SEAL: CELANESE 23593, REPLACED WITH C.T.S. 741

column168: PATTY, SALT LAKE CITY INTERMODAL RAMP, REPORTED CONTAINER EMPU 286146 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE REAR DOORS.  THE CONTAINER WAS A LOAD OF CLEANING LIQUIDS AND CONTAINS SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  THE CONTAINER WAS LOCATED AT THE HAZMAT SECTION OF THE RAMP AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS. HARRY RODABOUGH, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED. MGR. RODABOUGH CONTRACTED WITH PACIFIC WEST, A UPRR CONTRACTOR, TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL AND CLEAN THE TRAILER.  THEY LOCATED 280 GALLON TOTES IN THE TRAILER THAT WERE DAMAGED AND THEY APPLIED FIELD PATCHES WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  THEY THEN REMEDIATED THE GROUND SPILL, REMOVING APPROXIMATELY TWO TO THREE CUBIC YARDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL.  TOTAL LOSS OF MATERIAL ESTIMATED AT TWO HUNDRED GALLONS.  THERE WAS NO SIGN OF BLOCKING OR BRACING IN THE LOAD.  WHEN THE SHIPPER CAME TO TAKE THE TRAILER, IN THE DOCKING PROCEDURE, THEY ROUGH HANDLED IT CAUSING ONE OF THE CONTAINERS TO START LEAKING AGAIN.  PACIFIC WEST RETURNED AND RE-APPLIED A FIELD PATCH. THE LOAD WAS SCHEDULED TO LEAVE THE YARD ON MONDAY THE THIRD OF FEBRUARY.

column168: UPRR'S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE A SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A TANK CAR VENTING IN OR NEAR NEFF YARD IN KANSAS CITY, MO.  MR SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH PATRICK CAMPBELL, CAR FOREMAN, AND DETERMINED THAT CARMEN WORKING AN ADJACENT TRACK HAD OBSERVED A TANK CAR IN THE MKCCB-29 THAT HAD PASSED THEM AND APPEARED TO BE VENTING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  MR. SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH THE KC METRO DISPATCHER AND HAD THE TRAIN STOPPED.  HE ALSO CONTACTED HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TO DISPATCH A RESPONDER TO INSPECT AND EVALUATE THE CAR TO DETERMINE THE PROBLEM AS MR. SEKAVEC WAS IN PINE BLUFF, AR.  PRIOR TO THE ARRIVAL OF GARY BUCKLAND WITH HAZ-MAT RESPONSE, THE TRAIN WAS MOVED TO FAIRFAX AND THE CAR WAS SET OUT.  MR. BUCKLAND MADE CONTACT WITH MAURICE MITCHELL, SR. MTO, AND THEY PROCEEDED TO THE CAR.  MR. BUCKLAND DONNED APPROPRIATE PPE AND CLIMBED THE CAR TO PERFORM THE INSPECTION.  HE FOUND THAT THE HINGE SIDE OF THE QUICK-FILL HOLE SECUREMENT LOCKING BAR WAS COMPLETELY GONE.  THE TWO "NUBS" THAT THE BAR IS NORMALLY BOLTED THROUGH WERE BOTH COMPLETELY CORRODED AWAY.  THE BOLT SIDE OF THE BAR WAS SECURED BUT THE LID, FOR ALL INTENTS, WAS TOTALLY UNSECURED.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE YARD AND SECURED SO THAT IT WOULD NOT BE MOVED OR CONTINUE ON IN TRANSPORTATION.  THE SHIPPER (JONES-HAMILTON) WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED WHAT THE PROBLEM WAS WITH THE CAR AND THAT WOULD BE VERIFIED AS SOON AS MR. SEKAVEC RETURNED TO KANSAS CITY.  MR. SEKAVEC INSPECTED CAR ON JANUARY 30TH ON HIS ARRIVAL IN KANSAS CITY.  HE WAS ABLE TO VERIFY THAT THE FILL COVER WAS NOT SECURED.  THE SHIPPER SENT A REPRESENTATIVE OUT FROM TOLEDO, OH, ON SUNDAY, FEBRUARY 2, 2003.  HE AND MR. SEKAVEC PROCEEDED TO THE CAR.  THE REPRESENTATIVE BROUGHT A NEW MANWAY COVER, FILL HOLE LID AND SECUREMENT BAR.  THE REPLACEMENT PARTS WERE INSTALLED AND THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVEMENT.  THE SHIPPER WILL OBTAIN A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT AUTHORITY PRIOR TO THE CAR BEING ALLOWED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

SAM, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR ACFX 76886 WAS LEAKING. THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 307, 19TH FROM THE NORTH END.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.  KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER SIMPSON INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT IT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE BLIND FLANGE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  HE SUSPECTED THAT THERE WAS A DEFECTIVE GASKET ON THE BLIND FLANGE.  HE WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE LEAK AND ADVISED THAT THE TANKCAR WOULD NEED TO BE TRANSLOADED.  CHEMTREC AND LOCAL RESPONSE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.  TERRY BOER, MILLINEUM, SHIPPER WAS ALSO CONTACTED.  MANAGER SIMPSON CONTRACTED WITH THE CENTER OF TOXICOLOGY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH FOR AIR QUALITY MONITORING.  THE PRODUCT, WHICH LEAKED AT A RATE OF THREE GALLONS PER MINUTE WAS CONTAINED IN ONE HUNDRED GALLON DRUMS.  TRANSLOADING OF PRODUCT WAS COMPLETED ON 2/1/03 AT 5:40 PM.

JOE CAFFIN, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS, REPORTED WHEN YARD CREWS WERE MOVING TANKCAR UTLX 203707 PRODUCT WAS SLOSHING OUT OF THE TOP AND RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE.  THE TANKCAR ONLY LEAKED WHEN MOVED.  IT HAD BEEN ISOLATED ON A YARD TRACK IN THE MIDDLE OF THE MASON CITY YARD.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS.  MIKE KOSCINSKI, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, REPORTED HE SPOKE WITH JOE CAFFIN, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS.  MR. CAFFIN HAD REPORTED THE PROBLEM TO A REPRESENTATIVE FROM MGP, MIDWEST GRAIN PROCESSORS, THE SHIPPER.  LARRY WILDER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, SPOKE WITH DAVE, PLANT MANAGER - MGP, WHO REPORTED MGP PERSONNEL WERE ENROUTE TO THE MASON CITY YARD.  MGR. WILDER REPORTED THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED ON SCENE AND INSPECTED THE TANK CAR.  THEY DISCOVERED THAT THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED THE BOLTS AND THE CAR RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: AT 0210HRS ON 1-5-03, CTS MGR LERCH WAS ADVISED BY THE RMCC OF A LEAKING TANK CAR UTLX 12284 LOCATED IN SETTEGAST YARD; HOUSTON, TX.  THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED IN THE LEY ROAD TEAM TRACK.  UPON ARRIVAL MGR LERCH NOTED A SLIGHT RELEASE OF PRODUCT ON THE SIDES OF THE CAR WITH NO EXPOSURE TO THE GROUND.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS SHIFTED, AND WAS NOT ALIGNED PROPERLY TO SEAL THE CAR.  ADDITIONALLY THE GASKET WAS PINCHED IN POSITION BY THE MANWAY COVER, AND WAS WORN.  MGR LERCH REPLACED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET, CLOSED AND TIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER WHICH SECURED THE CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION.  ON 1-6-03, MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, CHENGXING AMERICA AND ADVISED MR CHECK SCHWARTZ; VICE PRESIDENT, OF THE INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED, AND NO REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  ORIGINAL SEALS PROTECTING: MANWAY: OT 122577, REPLACED WITH UPRR CTS-0008435 COMBINATION HOUSING: OT 122578, REPLACED WITH UPRR CTS 0008469 BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE: OT 122579

AT 1715HRS ON 1-6-03, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THE FOLLOWING.  MGR INTERMODAL OPERATIONS, JOE PEREZ HAD REPORTED CONTAINER OOLU 334583 LOCATED IN LOT 5, ENGLEWOOD INTERMODAL FACILITY; HOUSTON, TX., TO BE LEAKING.  DURING INSPECTION, MGR LERCH NOTED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF LIQUID TO HAVE LEAKED FROM THE FRONT OF THE CONTAINER THROUGH THE WOODEN CONTAINER FLOOR.  PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WAS DRY, HOWEVER THE CONTAINER FLOORING WAS DAMP.  MGR LERCH APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA TO CONTAIN ANY FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  EFFORTS TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER, CSX INTERMODAL WERE MADE, AND AFTER SEVERAL UNSUCCESSFUL ATTEMPTS WERE MADE, MGR LERCH AND MR PEREZ AGREED THEY WOULD CONTACT THE SHIPPER THE FOLLOWING MORNING TO DETERMINE WHAT CORRECTIVE ACTION THE SHIPPER WOULD TAKE.  AT 0800 HRS ON 1-7-03, CTS MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, CSX INTERMODAL AND SPOKE TO HAZMAT MANAGER MARK MULLIS.  AFTER ADVISING MR MULLIS, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN, DECONTAMINATE, AND REMEDIATE THE RELEASE.  AT 0930HRS, HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ARRIVED ON SCENE AND BEGAN WORKING ON CONTAINER OOLU 33458.  CONTAINER WAS LOADED WITH PALLETS STACKED 2 HIGH AND 2 ACROSS, LOADED FULL FRONT TO REAR.  EACH PALLET WAS LOADED WITH FORTY, 30 LB BAGS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLID THAT WERE SHRINK WRAPPED.  AFTER UNLOADING OF THE CONTAINER, TWO 30LB BAGS OF PRODUCT WERE FOUND ON THE LOWER LEFT FRONT PALLET TO HAVE BEEN PUNCTURED FROM IMPROPER LOADING.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT MIXED WITH CONDENSATION WITHIN THE TRAILER WHICH THEN LEAKED THROUGH THE FLOOR.  AFTER DETERMINING THE SOURCE AND CAUSE OF THE RELEASE, THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND CONTAINED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE CONTAINER WAS DECONTAMINATED, CLEANED AND WILL BE SHOPPED FOR A DEFECTIVE LEFT DOOR HASP. THE LADING WAS THEN RE-LOADED INTO CONTAINER OOLU 337899, RE-BILLED AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED, AND NO REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  ORIGINAL PROTECTING SEAL: UP-4240855; CONTAINER OOLU 334583.  REPLACEMENT SEAL APPLIED: UPRR CTS 0006192; CONTAINER OOLU 337899.

HARRY RODABOUGH, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED A DIESEL FUEL RELEASE FROM TANKCAR NATX 78267 DURING LOADING OPERATIONS AT THE CHEVRON REFINERY AT 2500 NORTH AT 1000 WEST IN NORTH SALT LAKE CITY, UT. THE TANKCAR BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE HEATER COIL ASSEMBLY. PERSONNEL FROM THE CHEVRON REFINERY HAD ISOLATED THE TANKCAR ON A HAZMAT PAD AREA AND HAD ALREADY STOPPED THE LEAK AND CLEANED UP THE AREA. MR RODABOUGH MADE ARRANGEMENT FOR THE TANKCAR TO BE INSPECTED AND REPAIRED. ON 01/10/2003 A TRANSLOAD OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONDUCTED, REMOVING APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF LOAD OF DIESEL FUEL FROM TANKCAR NATX78263. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE LEAKING CAR NATX 78267 HAD A HOLE IN THE HEATER PIPE AT A POINT NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKCAR. ALL CLEAN-UP AND NOTIFICATIONS WERE THE RESPONSIBILITY OF CHEVRON PRODUCTS COMPANY. THE CAR IS A UNION PACIFIC LEASE CAR USED TO MOVE DIESEL FUEL TO ELKO NEVADA FOR USE BY THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: ANGEL BALLESTEROS, FOREMAN GENERAL, REPORTED A CARMAN COMPLAINED OF INHALATION DUE TO TANKAR NATX24943 WHICH CONTAINS TOLUENE WASTE AT THE TUCSON REPAIR TRACK. MR.BALLESTEROS REQUESTED DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, TO BE NOTIFIED. MR. BALLESTEROS REPORTED HE AND THE CARMEN WERE AT THE UNIVERSITY MEDICAL CENTER IN TUCSON. DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED. UPON MR JOHNSON'S ARRIVAL HE CONDUCTED AN INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR AND FOUND THAT THE MANWAY BOLTS SECURING THE MANWAY WERE LESS THAT WRENCH TIGHT AND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS DETERIORATED AND CUT IN TWO LOCATIONS. REPAIRS CONSISTED OF APPLING A NEW GASKET AND SECURING THE MANWAY PROPERLY.

UPRR'S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A TANK CAR VENTING IN PROVISO YARD. ACFX 95693, LOAD OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS REPORTED TO BE VENTING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR. MR. SEKAVEC CONTACTED JUSTIN NEWCOM, MYO, WHO ADVISED THAT HE HAD THE CAR ISOLATED IN THE YARD. HE ALSO ADVISED THE CAR WAS VENTING WHILE SITTING STILL BUT WORSENED WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED. MR.SEKACVEC CONTACTED TRANS ENVIRONMENTAL FOR A RESPONSE TO EVALUATE THE CAR AND MAKE REPAIRS IF POSSIBLE. MR. SEKAVEC ALSO HAD RMCC CONTACT THE SHIPPER (ATOFINA CHEMICAL) VIA CHEMTREC TO ADVISE THEM OF THE SITUATION. WHEN TRANS ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL ARRIVED, THEY ASSESSED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE HINGED MANWAY COVER WAS IN POSITION AND THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE ALL IN A UPRIGHT POSITION. HOWEVER, THE SWING BOLTS WERE ALL ONLY HAND TIGHT. THEY TIGHTENED ALL OF THE BOLTS AND SECURED THE CAR. THEY ALSO WIPED THE CAR DOWN TO REMOVE ANY OF THE RESIDUE THAT HAD SPLASHED OUT OF THE CAR. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FROM TRANSPORTATION. NO MATERIAL REACHED THE GROUND AND THERE IS NO OTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT EXPECTED FROM THIS INCIDENT.

GATX 54226 REPORTED LEAKING AT UPRR YARD IN EL PASO. JOHN JACKSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MR. JACKSON REPORTED TEN GALLONS RELEASED DUE TO MISSING LIQUID EDUCTION LINE VALVE. MR. JACKSON INSTALLED A COUPLING AND SECURED THE LIQUID LINE WITH A PLUG, HAD THE CAR MOVED TO A SECURE TRACK IN THE ALFALFA YD, NOTIFIED SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC. SHIPPER NOTIFIED RESCAR CO. TO RESPOND/ REPLACED THE MISSING VALVE. RESCAR INSTALLED NEW LIQUID LINE VALVE ON 1/16/03 AND RINCHEM CO CLEANED RESIDUE FROM RELEASE ON THE OUTSIDE OF CAR. SHIPPING DESCRIPTION CORRECTED ON SHIPPING PAPER AND CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: MANAGER ERNIE SIROTEK WAS ADVISED THAT BOXCAR MP268303 WAS LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL FROM THE END OF THE CAR. TWO UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD EMPLOYEES WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR REPORTED EXPOSURE TO THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE BOXCAR WAS LOADED WITH 68 1-TON SUPER-SACKS. ACTUAL PHYSICAL INSPECTION TO DETERMINE CAUSE COULD NOT BE PERFORMED AT THIS LOCATION. THE BOX WAS TEMPORARILY REPAIRED AND ALLOWED TO MOVE TO DESTINATION. IT IS SUSPECTED THAT ONE OF THE SUPER-SACKS WAS TORN DURING THE LOADING OF THE CAR.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ED FEDRICK, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT (SAHM) REPORTED THE MANWAY COVER ON TANKCAR UTLX48759 LEAKED GASOLINE DUE TO LOOSE BOLTS. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AT THE RIVER YARD, NEAR MP 452 ON THE SHREVEPORT SUBDIVISION. THERE WERE NO LEAKS ONTO THE GROUND OR INTO WATERWAYS. THERE WERE NO REPORTS OF INJURIES. THE BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED. SAHM FEDRICK MADE STATE NOTIFICATION. RMCC MADE NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTREC (ERIC).

RAUL MEZA, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, REPORTED TANKCAR HWPX 000104 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT AT PORT LAREDO YARD, INTERSTATE 35 NORTH. THE CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED ON TRACK 505. MR. MEZA ADVISED THE LIQUID WAS LEAKING IN A STEADY STREAM FROM TWO OF THREE COMPARTMENTS ON THE TANKCAR, ONE FROM THE COMPARTMENT AT B END AND FROM THE TOP AND MIDDLE OF THE TANKCAR. MR MEZA ADVISED THE GASKET DID NOT APPEAR TO BE SEALING PROPERLY AND LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS ON THE BALLAST UNDERNEATH THE TANKCAR. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED FOR SHIPPER ASSISTANCE AND PAUL PERSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. ABSORBENT PADS WERE PLACED UNDER THE TANKCAR TO COLLECT THE LEAKING PRODUCT. SAHM MEZA LOCATED A LEAK FROM THE PACKING GLAND ON THE LIQUID LINE. THE TANKCAR APPEARED TO BE OVERFILLED. SAHM MEZA MET WITH ABEL GONZALEZ FROM OAKLEY TRANSPORT. MR GONZALEZ ADVISED THAT HE WAS THE ONE WHO HANDLED THE LOADING AT THEIR FACILITY PLANT. HE STATED THAT HE USUALLY TIMES THE FILLING, BUT MAY HAVE LOST TRACK AND OVERFILLED THE TANK, COMPARTMENTS. DURING AN INSPECTION OF THE CAMLOK COVER ON THE LIQUID LINE THE GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE. ALSO THERE WAS NOT SUFFICIENT OUTAGE AND PRODUCT WAS OVERFLOWING. MR GONZALEZ REMOVED SOME OF THE PRODUCT AND APPLIED A NEW GASKET WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. TANK CAR WAS RELEASED ABOUT 2000HRS. WITHOUT INCIDENT.

NICKI, CHEMTREC, REPORTED SHE RECEIVED A CALL FROM A MOTORIST IN BOSSIER CITY. THE MOTORIST REPORTED AS SHE WAS WAITING FOR A TRAIN TO CLEAR THE CROSSING SHE OBSERVED WHAT APPEARED TO BE SOMETHING DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANKCAR GATX 44015. THE TANKCAR WAS TRACED AND SHOWED TO BE A LOAD OF CORROSIVE LIQUIDS WHICH WAS ON TRAIN MPBEW 21. TERMINAL TRAIN DISPATCHER 28 DETERMINED THAT THE TRAIN WAS IN THE SHREVEPORT YARD. ED FEDRICK, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SHREVEPORT YARD. NICKI, CHEMTREC, ISSUED REPORT NUMBER 01212003036 FOR THE INCIDENT. SAHM FEDRICK REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 44015 HAD BEEN SET OUT AT THE RIVER YARD IN SHERVEPORT, LA AND THE STATE POLICE/HAZMAT OFFICER WAS ENROUTE TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE. SAHM FEDRICK ADVISED THAT THEIR INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE STUFFING BOX WAS LOOSE. THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS TIGHTENED AND THE TANKCAR RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY MYO DAVE WILLOUGHBE, REPORTING TANK CAR GATX 10071 WAS PULLED FROM THE NALCO PLANT WITH THE OFF LOADING HOSES STILL CONNECTED. MET WITH MTO WILLOUGHBE AND THE NALCO PLANT REPRESENTATIVES TO INSPECT THE SITE. THE NALCO RACK HAS A CONTAINMENT AREA, AND WHEN THE CAR WAS PULLED THE 2 INCH HOSE LINE BROKE THE CONNECTION NIPPLE OFF THE LOADING RACK PIPING. THE TANK CAR VALVES HAD BEEN CLOSED, AND THE LOADING RACK LINES WERE CLOSED. APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF SOAP PRODUCT, NALCO STARBREX ST20, DRAINED FROM THE BROKEN HOSE LINES INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA. A SMALL DRIBBLE TRAIL OF PRODUCT WAS NOTED ACROSS THE PAVEMENT AT THE REAR OF THE PLANT, APPROXIMATELY 200 FEET, WHERE THE HOSE DRUG ALONG THE GROUND UNTIL THE SWITCH CREW NOTICED IT AND STOPPED. NALCO PLANT PERSONNEL REMOVED THE HOSE FROM THE TANK CAR AND PROCEEDED TO REMEDIATE THE CONTAINMENT PIT AND PAVED PARKING AREA. THERE WAS NO BLUE FLAG ON THE TRACK SHOWING THE CAR WAS STILL CONNECTED, AND THE SWITCH CREW FAILED TO NOTE THE HOSE LINE CONNECTED TO THE TANK CAR PRIOR TO MOVING IT. NALCO REPLACED THE HOSE CONNECTION TO THE UNLOADING RACK AND IS IN THE PROCESS OF ORDERING BLUE FLAGS FOR THE TRACK.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: WILLIAM MALLOY, CHEYENNE YARDMASTER, REPORTED A SWITCH CREW DISCOVERED TANKCAR NATX 29608 LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR WHILE IT WAS BEING MOVED. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS AND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AT THE WEST END OF YARD 1 TRACK 807. MARK ROSS, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONTRACTED WITH RMCAT, ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. ABSORBENT PADS WERE PLACED UNDER THE CAR TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT. NOTIFICATION WERE MADE TO THE STATE AND CHEMTREC. INSPECTION BY THE CONTRACTOR DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID VALVE WAS CLOSED, HOWEVER, THE CLOSURE PLUG WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE PLUG WAS SECURED AND THE CAR RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

AT 0850HRS ON 1-27-03, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT BRIAN RICHARD, DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS HAD REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 42221 TO BE LEAKING. CAR WAS LOCATED IN TRACK 19, SETTEGAST YARD;HOUSTON, TX UPON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF CAR, MGR LERCH NOTED SIDES OF CAR TO BE MOIST FROM SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT. CAUSE OF RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FAILED VACUUM RELIEF VALVE LOCATED ON THE MANWAY COVER. AFTER DETERMINING SOURCE OF RELEASE,MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, AND SPOKE TO PATTY PHILPOTT SAFETY COORDINATOR, ONEDO NALCO ADVISING HER OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE SHIPPER INSPECT THE CAR. UPON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF THE CAR BY ONDEO NALCO PERSONNEL, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THEY WOULD HAVE HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN AND NEUTRALIZE THE CAR AND SPILL SITE, AND HAVE RESCAR REPLACE THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE ON 1-28-03. THE SHIPPER SECURED A TEMPORARY PATCH TO THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER RELEASE. MGR LERCH THEN HAD THE CAR SET-OUT TO AN ADJACENT ISOLATION TRACK. ON 1-28-03, HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL AND RESCAR MOBILE RAILCAR REPAIR ARRIVED ON SCENE. THE CAR WAS CLEANED AND THE AFFECTED AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED BY HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL. RESCAR MOBIL REPAIR REPLACED THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. AFTER THE CAR WAS PROPERLY SECURED, CTS MGR LERCH RELEASED THE CAR TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS AFFECTED, NOR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column168: TIM POST, ASSISTANT YARD MANAGER REPORTED A SMALL LEAK FROM THE LEFT REAR CORNER OF CONTAINER HLXU 404985, AT ICTF YARD, AND STATED THE CONTAINER WAS PRESENTLY LOCATED ON GREEN ROW, SPOT 468. THE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING AT THE RATE OF ONE DRIP EVERY THREE MINUTES, WITH A SIX INCH PUDDLE ON THE ASPHALT PAD UNDER THE CONTAINER. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. HE MET STEVE WITTMAN, CONTRACTOR FOR INDUSTRIAL WASTE UTILIZATION, TO REMEDIATE THE LEAKING CONTAINER FOR THE SHIPPER, SUNKIST. RMCC MADE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS TO CHEMTREC, CES, AND A COURTESY NOTIFICATION TO LOS ANGELES CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT. INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS NOTED THE ENTIRE LADING OF 55 GALLON METAL DRUMS, FLOOR LOADED WITH A VOID OF SEVERAL FEET AT THE REAR DOORS. THE VOID AREA HAD SEVERAL USED PALLETS PLACED ON THE FLOOR TO PREVENT THE DRUMS FROM SHIFTING. APPROXIMATELY 16 DRUMS AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED TO THE REAR, IMPACTING THE PALLETS, CAUSING SUBSTANTIAL DAMAGE TO THE LOWER THIRD OF THE SIDEWALLS. TWO DRUMS WERE FOUND LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIMES WERE THE SIDEWALL OF THE DRUM WAS SO DEFLECTED INWARD THAT THE METAL WAS PULLING APART AT THE CHIME. ESTIMATED 2-3 GALLONS WAS LOST FROM EACH DRUM. THE DRUMS WERE INVERTED AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT. WHILE INSPECTING THE REMAINING DRUMS, AN ADDITIONAL 12 DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE SO SEVERELY DAMAGED THAT THEY WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR ANY FURTHER TRANSIT. VIRTUALLY EVERY DRUM IN THE LOAD HAD SOME FORM OF DAMAGE, AND THE SEVERELY DAMAGED 12 DRUMS REQUIRED OVER PACKING IN SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT PRIOR TO ANY ADDITIONAL TRANSPORTATION. THE ENTIRE LOAD OF DRUMS AND OVER PACKED DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO A HIGHWAY TRAILER FOR OVER THE ROAD TRANSPORT BACK TO THE SHIPPER, SUNKIST GROWER. DEVELOPED INFORMATION THAT THIS CONTAINER ORIGINATED FROM THE SUNKIST FACILITY, ONTARIO, CA, AND MOVED BY RAIL ON 12-24-02 FROM LONG BEACH, CA, TO BARBOURS CUT, TEXAS, WHERE THE CONTENTS WERE FOUND TO BE DAMAGED UPON ARRIVAL. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO SENT THE ENTIRE LOAD BACK TO LONG BEACH, WHERE THE LOAD WAS NOTED LEAKING.

column168: DELIVERY WAS MADE ON JANUARY 30TH, 2003 FOR 227.7 GALLONS OF KEROSENE. TANK IS LOCATED UNDER THE MOBILE HOME BEHIND SKIRTING. FILL PIPE IS LOCATED OUTSIDE OF TRAILER SKIRTING. TANK WHISTLE AND VENT ARE LOCATED ON TOP OF TANK BUT NOT VENTED TO OUTSIDE.DRIVER FILLED TANK AND LISTENED FOR WHISTLE TO STOP. ON THE EVENING OF JANUARY 30, 2003, THE SERVICE TECHNICIAN RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE BURN'S RESIDENCE COMPLAINING OF FUMES IN THEIR HOME. TECHNICIAN ARRIVED AND REMOVED SKIRTING AND WHILE INSPECTING THE TANK, FOUND IT TO BE DAMP ON TOP AS WELL AS THE SOIL DIRECTLY BELOW IT. TECHNICIAN APPLIED OIL DRY AND SORBET PADS ON THE AROUND THE TANK. JANUARY 31ST, 2003 WE BEGAN TO PUMP OFF THE TANK INTO DRUMS AND FINAL TRANSFER INTO OUR DELIVERY TRUCK. LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED AND CONSULTED ON WHAT WE COULD DO. THEY RECOMMENDED REMOVING THE SOURCE AND VENTILATION. BRANDO SMITH, OPERATIONS MANAGER FROM LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL, CAME OUT WITH A PID TO TAKE SOME PRELIMINARY READINGS PRIOR TO TANK REMOVAL AND EXCAVATION. WE REMOVED THE TANK FROM UNDER THE TRAILER AND BEGAN TO EXCAVATE THE AREA. RETURN TO THE SITE MONDAY FEBRUARY 3, 2003 TO CONTINUE EXCAVATING THE AREA. LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL RETURNED FEBRUARY 4TH 2003 TO TAKE MORE EXTENSIVE TEST OF THE AREA. SEE ATTACHED DOCUMENTATION OF TEST RESULTS. THE AREAS THAT REQUIRED ADDITIONAL EXCAVATION WERE COMPLETED ON FEBRUARY 5TH. LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL IS SCHEDULED TO RETURN TO RETEST SAMPLE AREA 19,25,28 AND 29. IT WAS DECIDED TO TAKE A COMPOSITE SOIL SAMPLE OF THE WHOLE EXCAVATED AREA ON FEBRUARY 10TH 2003. THE SAMPLES HAVE COME BACK WITH NON-DETECTABLE LEVELS OF CONTAMINATION THE COMPLETE REPORT FROM LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL IS ATTACHED. A TANK HAD BEEN INSTALLED OUTSIDE THE TRAILER WITH A PROPER FILL AND VENT. THE EXCAVATED SOIL IS PRESENTLY STORED AT 130 SOUTH CHURCH STREET IN PARKESBURG PA 19365. THE SOIL WILL BE PROPERLY CONTAINED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL DISPOSAL PAPERS WILL BE AVAILABLE FOR THE DEP IF REQUESTED.

column168: THE FELICIA OIL TRUCK DELIVERED 150 GALLONS OF NO.2 FUEL TO 9 BEACON STREET, GLOUCESTER, MA. ON JANUARY 13, 2003.  IT WAS THE WRONG DELIVERY ADDRESS.  THE OIL TANK AT 9 BEACON STREET HAD BEEN REMOVED BY PERSONS UNKNOWN, BUT THE VENT AND FILL WERE LEFT IN TACK TO THE OUTSIDE WALL OF THE HOUSE.  RESIDENTS OF THE PROPERTY WERE NOT AT HOME AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY. UPON THEIR RETURN, THEY NOTICED A SMELL OF FUEL AND NOTIFIED THE GLOUCESTER FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE FELICIA OIL WAS NOTIFIED BY THE DEPARTMENT AS THE DELIVER TICKET WAS IN THE MAIL BOX.  FELICIA OIL NOTIFIED THE EPA, NOT REALIZING THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ALREADY DONE SO.  WE BEGAN CLEANING UP THE SPILL, ALL OF WHICH HAD GONE INTO A WATERPROOF CISTERN IN THE CELLAR. WE PUMPED BETWEEN 132 AND 148 GALLONS OF FUEL AND PLACED IT INTO DRUMS.  WE CLEANED UP THE DEBRIS AND PUT IT INTO HEAVY, DOUBLE PLASTIC BAGS.  WE CALLED IN CLEAN HARBORS AS REQUESTED BY CHRISTOPHER BRESNAHAN, ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER EMERGENCY RESPONSE.  CLEAN UP WAS TAKEN OUT OF OUR HANDS AND TAKEN OVER BY CLEAN HARBORS UNDER THE DIRECTION OF STEVE FLEMING. CLEAN HARBORS SIGNED OFF ON MARCH 20, 2003.  THE COST OF THE CLEANUP WAS APPROXIMATELY $17,000.  ACTIONS TAKEN. - WE REMOVED THE FILL AND VENT FROM THE HOUSE AND DISPOSED OF IT.  ALL MANIFESTS ETC. WERE TURNED OVER TO OUR INSURANCE COMPANY WHO PAID ALL EXPENSES FOR THE CLEANUP.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT OF AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANK CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S  AMPTHILL, VA PLANT.  THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA, AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS IN QUESTION HAD EXPERIENCED ANY UNUSUAL HANDLING OR HARD COUPLING'S IN TRANSIT.  CSXT WITH OLIN'S CORPORATION HAD INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S. THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR.
